May be a naive question but this is one thing I’m not fully understanding about AI. 

To me it seems that AI is a command taker. ChatGPT is asked a question and given a command and will answer logically based on its algorithms and data models. 

What exactly needs to happen here for AI to take over and act maliciously? 

How can a logical command taker break free of this and essentially become disobedient? 

@DavidDeutschOxf mentioned that the power of humans is that we are disobedient and that’s why AI will at least to our current understanding, most likely not “take over”. 

Thoughts?

Chat gpt asked me to verify my humanity twice to log in m8 ur not human fuck off

I moved on and asked ChatGPT to make a shapes.txt file and reference the stop_times.txt. ChatGPT did end up working on a shapes.txt file, but also got stuck in a loop. The actual location of the shape it drew was... off. The pic with the map shows the shape in purple. 9/n https://t.co/RgxMIUnPs3

Now I asked ChatGPT to make the stop_times.txt file. It began creating a nice stop_times.txt file, but then got itself stuck in a seemingly endless loop of going back and forth. (it only needs to do one out-and-back for it to work). 8/n https://t.co/JfJ4gaQN4M
@VergaraLautaro ChatGPT learns fundamental theorem of Arithmetic... (Nothing special about 793) https://t.co/fwpkXul0TD

I think the ferry doesn't necessarily stick to a schedule while operating, so I asked ChatGPT to create the trips.txt and frequencies.txt file. It initially made up some frequencies that changed thru the day, but eventually made one for 30-minute service. 7/n https://t.co/SHo0hw3U14
Now for the calendar. ChatGPT initially created the calendar files for a 2022 schedule and excluded July 4 until I asked for that to be included. 6/n https://t.co/RxXHLDwlcx

Next up, stops.txt. ChatGPT created the file with the 3 docks including the GPS coords. However, upon inspection, the GPS coords were out in the ocean, not in the harbor. I verified using https://t.co/0HI7U0N25y. The 3 stops are the markers and the harbor is in the rectangle. 5/n https://t.co/ybPxndUNHy

It also made the routes.txt file, but I had to remind ChatGPT that including the agency_id is a best practice. ChaptGPT confirmed this best practice and added in the agency_id. 4/n https://t.co/itUWpRJj4T

...ChapGPT had no problem creating an agency.txt file. 😎 So it was off to the races with creating each file individually.  It also provided some helpful documentation of this file. I mistakenly thought it was agencies.txt and ChatGPT went along with me. 😄 3/n https://t.co/L56lWbLTyZ

The Santa Cruz Harbor Ferry is a seasonal service that takes people between 3 docks. https://t.co/mXNkeEEcHe

To start, I tried to see if given just the text describing the service if ChatGPT would be able to do it all at once. No such luck, unfortunately, but... 2/n https://t.co/89IOoeMkdR

ChatGPT explains Ayn Rand's epistemology quite well:
"Rand's epistemology was based on the idea that we form concepts by abstracting from the perceptual data provided by our senses, and that we can use logic to integrate and validate our concepts. She called this process "conceptual algebra", because it involves using symbols (words) to represent units (things or groups of things) that share some common characteristic, and manipulating these symbols according to certain rules (definitions and principles) to reach new conclusions. For example, we can form the concept of "dog" by observing different dogs and noticing their common features, such as having four legs, fur, and barking. We can then use this concept to communicate with others, to identify new dogs, or to compare dogs with other animals. Rand argued that conceptual algebra is the only valid method of cognition, and that it is based on the objective reality that exists independently of our consciousness."

Once upon a time, in a lush forest, lived an opossum named Opsec. Opsec was no ordinary opossum, as he was always alert and cautious, making sure that he didn't fall prey to any of the predators that roamed the forest.

One day, as Opsec was foraging for food, he came across a group of animals who were discussing how they could keep themselves safe from the hunters who roamed the forest. Opsec, being the cautious and alert opossum that he was, immediately offered his services to help the group.

Opsec shared his knowledge of security and taught the group about the importance of keeping their personal information and belongings safe. He showed them how to hide their food, cover their tracks, and avoid leaving any traces of their presence in the forest.

The group of animals was amazed at Opsec's knowledge and skills, and they decided to name him the Chief Security Officer (CSO) of the forest. Opsec was proud of his new title, and he continued to educate and help the other animals in the forest.

Opsec soon became a legend in the forest, and animals from far and wide came to seek his advice on how to stay safe and secure. He was known as the protector of the forest, and he took his role very seriously.

Years passed, and Opsec grew old, but his knowledge and wisdom continued to inspire the animals in the forest. Opsec may have left the forest, but his legacy lived on, as the animals continued to use the techniques and strategies that he had taught them to keep themselves safe and secure.

And so, the forest remained a safe and secure place for all the animals, thanks to the teachings of Opsec, the opossum who was always alert and cautious, and who became the protector of the forest.

Which is better, ChatGPT or Bard?

ChatGPT and Bard are both large language models (LLMs) that are trained on massive amounts of text data. They can both generate text, translate languages, write different kinds of creative content, and answer your questions in an informative way. However, there are some key differences between the two models.

ChatGPT is a chatbot that is designed to be a conversational partner. It can hold conversations about a variety of topics, and it can generate text that is creative and engaging. However, ChatGPT is not as well-suited for tasks that require factual accuracy or in-depth knowledge.

Bard is a language model that is designed to be a "creative companion." It can help you with tasks such as writing creative content, translating languages, and generating different kinds of text formats. Bard is also better at tasks that require factual accuracy or in-depth knowledge.

Ultimately, the best model for you will depend on your specific needs. If you are looking for a conversational partner, ChatGPT is a good option. 

If you are looking for a language model that can help you with tasks that require factual accuracy or in-depth knowledge, Bard is a better option.

Why GPT-4 (ChatGPT) isn’t AGI 
(its own explanation) 
***
GPT-4, like its predecessor GPT-3, is not considered an Artificial General Intelligence (AGI). AGI refers to a machine or software that can perform any intellectual task that a human being can do, demonstrating a level of autonomy, understanding, and adaptability similar to human intelligence.
GPT-4, though more advanced than GPT-3, still falls short of AGI for several reasons:

1. Limited understanding: GPT-4 can generate coherent and contextually relevant responses, but its understanding is limited by the patterns and associations it has learned from the text during training. It lacks true comprehension and the ability to reason about the content it generates.

2. Lack of common sense: GPT-4 can make mistakes that a human with common sense would not make. It may produce answers that are incorrect or nonsensical, even if they appear plausible at first glance.

3. Narrow domain: While GPT-4 can perform well across a wide range of tasks, it is not capable of performing all intellectual tasks. It is primarily a text-based AI and cannot, for example, directly engage in complex spatial reasoning or create new inventions.

4. Lack of adaptability: GPT-4 has a fixed architecture and cannot easily adapt to new tasks or environments without significant retraining. It lacks the ability to learn from its mistakes or build upon its knowledge in real-time like a human would.

5. No self-awareness: GPT-4 does not possess self-awareness or consciousness. It does not have an understanding of its own existence or the ability to reflect on its actions or motivations. This is a crucial aspect of human intelligence that is not present in GPT-4.

6. Task and goal orientation: Unlike humans, GPT-4 does not have the ability to set its own goals or have a purpose. It is designed to perform tasks given to it by users, and it cannot autonomously generate its own objectives or motivations.

7. Emotion and empathy: GPT-4 is not capable of experiencing emotions or empathizing with others, which are essential components of human intelligence. It can generate text that appears to convey emotions, but it does not actually feel or understand those emotions.

8. Creativity: While GPT-4 can produce impressive and creative text outputs, its creativity is limited by the patterns it has learned from its training data. It cannot generate truly original ideas or concepts that are not present in its training data.

In summary, GPT-4 is an advanced language model with impressive capabilities, but it is not an Artificial General Intelligence.

No need for simple link pages like Linktree when you can tell ChatGPT to make a fully custom link page for you.

ChatGPT will give you the HTML code, paste that in a text doc, save it as .html, and open that to test it in your browser. When you're ready, just upload it to a cheap web host, DONE.

Edit the headline, image URL, bio, and links to be yours, and change the colors and fonts to whatever you like. 

It even has a gradient headline color and the buttons change color on hover 🤯

If you don't like how something looks, keep talking to ChatGPT about what you want to change and it will keep revising it.

PROMPT:

Create a mobile-responsive HTML page with a container with a maximum width 600px and top margin of at least 50px. 

The page should have a black background. The flex container has a white background with rounded edges.

The container has a headline text, a round headshot image, a short bio text, and buttons. 

The headshot should be no larger than 250px

Below the headshot, there should be a short bio. The container should have a maximum text width of 600px.

The centered vertical column of the container should have rounded. The buttons align  vertically and the buttons have consistent matching widths and are contained within the container.

.
①問題の分解で、適切な質問を選択する
.
問題を解決するためには、まず問題を分解し、適切な質問を選択することが重要だ。これにより、ChatGPTに対して、情報を効率的に得ることができる。問題の分解能力はプログラミング的思考の根幹であり、ChatGPTとの対話の際にも非常に役立つ。
.
②アルゴリズム思考で、手順やルールを指示する
.
アルゴリズム思考は、手順やルールを明確に指示する能力だ。ChatGPTに対して、具体的な手順やルールを指示することで、より期待通りの回答が得られる。この能力は、プログラムの設計と同様に、ChatGPTとの対話でも効果的である。
.
③パターン認識で、得られた回答の構造を見つける
.
得られた回答の中から、パターンや構造を認識することで、ChatGPTがどのような回答を生成するか理解しやすくなる。このパターン認識能力は、プログラミング的思考の中でも重要な要素であり、そのためChatGPTとの対話を効果的に進めることができる。
.
④抽象化で、本質を捉え直す
.
抽象化は、具体的な事例から本質を捉える能力のこと。この能力があることで、得られた回答をもとに、ChatGPTの回答の本質を理解し、次の質問や指示をより効果的に行うことができる。この能力は、プログラミング的思考においても重要な役割を果たしている。
.
⑤デバッグと改善で、回答が期待通りになるよう質問や指示を調整し続ける
.
デバッグと改善は、回答が期待通りになるよう質問や指示を調整し続けるプロセスだ。ChatGPTとの対話では、これを繰り返すことでより良い回答が得られる。デバッグと改善のプロセスは、プログラミング的思考の中でも〝実践的な要素〟であり、これによりChatGPTとの対話をより効果的に進めることができる。

Question to #ChatGPT : 
how much wood could a wood chuck chuck, if a wood chuck could chuck wood?

Answer:
According to a popular tongue-twister, "How much wood would a woodchuck chuck, if a woodchuck could chuck wood?" While it's a fun question to ponder, the truth is that woodchucks, also known as groundhogs, do not actually chuck wood. They are burrowing animals and their primary activity is digging tunnels and burrows in soil. However, in 1988, a New York State wildlife expert estimated that a woodchuck could chuck approximately 700 pounds of dirt in the course of digging a burrow, but this estimate has not been scientifically verified. So while we don't have a definitive answer to the question of how much wood a woodchuck could chuck, it's safe to say that their expertise lies more in the realm of digging tunnels than chucking wood.

I've been on a quest to find more practical business use cases for ChatGPT so I'll be sharing more as we go.

How we're combining @Gong_io and ChatGPT to track client sentiment so we can level up client retention:

One of the gaps we've seen with client services over the years is the ability to track sentiment consistently.

People get busy with meetings, reporting, execution, etc. that sentiment tracking becomes an afterthought.

But what if you were able to see how clients were feeling each week with an automatic 1-10 score for each call? 10 being best.

If calls were 9-10, they'd be in the green. 🟢

If calls were 7-8, they'd be in the yellow. 🟡

If calls were 6 and below, they'd be in the red. 🔴

Then if they were yellow or red 3 weeks in a row, your team could jump in and do something about it before it became too late. << Stole this from @mattmochary's 'traffic lights' framework.

We combined Gong with ChatGPT to automatically track our calls. The data gets outputted into Slack and also into a spreadsheet so we can:

- See a quick summary of each call

- See the AI-scored call

- Determine if actions need to be taken

tl;dr If blockchain has no off switch, blockchain + AI may also have no off switch.

Longer argument

AI & crypto aren’t talked about in the same breath too often yet, but this may change soon. If anything, the pseudo-autonomous multi-agent systems that ChatGPT/LLMs open up are a strong case for why decentralized trust can enable that autonomy to extend into financial transactions fairly smoothly. (whether that’s good or bad is another story)

I am particularly concerned however with what this intersection implies about systemic vulnerabilities that cryptocurrency has introduced in the world.

To put it briefly, the digitization of real world monetary assets broke the ‘air gap’ that we had maintained between monetary assets and internet bits, prior to the adoption of bitcoin.

In relation to AI, this means that vulnerability to an AI system going awry moves from the avenue of content vulnerabilities (eg misinfo), to direct real world asset vulnerabilities (stealing/disappearing your money for one).

A more concerning edge case is that this combo introduces workarounds against an AI off switch. With existing LLM, cryptocurrency & DAO frameworks, it’s within reach to build a multi-agent system where stolen (or injected) crypto capital is escrowed, a DAO is programmed to use this capital as hostage/incentive for the robbed entities to keep an LLM instance on, to continuously replace it with newer versions with more data and more parameters, or even to follow a predefined roadmap for the additional abilities each new version is required to have. Or else no money. In other words, a digital whip.

The core breakthrough of cryptocurrency is the creation of a decentralized trust system with no central off switch. The same can easily be true of Crypto + AI.

(This systemic crypto vulnerability is akin to how vulnerable flights would be if plane flight systems were connected to the internet and remotely controllable. May theoretically make flying better and perhaps more resilient to human error, but in the process would remove the ‘air gap’ that separates flight software from the internet and keeps planes safer from software hacks)

Dans un pays lointain, où règne la démocratie,
Un président, soucieux de l'harmonie,
Gouvernait avec soin et sagesse infinie,
Pour le bien de son peuple et de l'économie.

Mais un jour, une loi controversée,
Fit débat au sein de la communauté,
Les députés, divisés et tourmentés,
N'arrivaient pas à un consensus pour l'adopter.

Le président, impatient et déterminé,
Pensa alors à une méthode peu appréciée,
Le fameux 49.3, outil autoritaire,
Pour imposer sa loi sans débat parlementaire.

Le peuple, mécontent de cette décision,
Manifesta sa colère et son indignation,
Les rues se remplirent de protestataires,
Dénonçant le pouvoir et l'injustice de l'affaire.

Le président, face à cette révolte soudaine,
Comprit qu'il avait fait une erreur de haine,
Il retira alors son usage du 49.3,
Et invita les députés à débattre en toute liberté.

Les députés, touchés par ce geste sincère,
Trouvèrent finalement un compromis éclair,
La loi fut adoptée, amendée et équilibrée,
Pour le bien de tous et dans l'unité.

Morale :
L'autorité sans dialogue mène à la discorde,
Cherche plutôt la concertation et l'accord,
Car c'est dans l'échange que l'on trouve la sagesse,
Et que l'on construit ensemble un monde de justice et de paix.

Elon Musk, along with other investors and researchers, founded OpenAI in December 2015 with the mission to ensure that artificial general intelligence (AGI) benefits all of humanity. Although Musk has invested millions of dollars into the organization, he chose not to exert control over it for a few reasons:

1. Broad benefit focus: OpenAI's primary mission is to ensure that AGI serves the interests of all of humanity. By not exerting direct control over OpenAI, Musk demonstrates his commitment to this broader mission and helps to establish trust that the organization will work in the best interests of the public, rather than being driven solely by the interests of its investors.

2. Safeguarding against concentration of power: OpenAI's Charter emphasizes a commitment to long-term safety and technical leadership. By ensuring that no single individual or entity has undue influence over the organization, OpenAI is better positioned to act independently, avoid conflicts of interest, and remain focused on its mission and safety research.

3. Collaboration with other research and policy institutions: OpenAI aims to create a global community to address the global challenges posed by AGI. By not controlling the organization, Musk helps to foster an environment that encourages collaboration with other research and policy institutions, and the sharing of knowledge and resources across the AI community.

4. Personal bandwidth and focus: Elon Musk has numerous other ventures that demand his attention, such as Tesla, SpaceX, Neuralink, and The Boring Company. By not exerting direct control over OpenAI, he can allocate more time and energy to these other projects while still supporting the development of AGI through his investment.

Overall, Elon Musk's decision not to exert control over OpenAI aligns with the organization's mission and principles, and it helps to create a more collaborative and inclusive environment within the AI research community.

5/ The Business Concept

Next, I got ChatGPT to do a SWOT analysis of my business idea and recommend the most time & cost effective business models considering the budget and time constraints.

The SWOT analysis was non-specific but the recommendations were pretty spot on. https://t.co/gE2LAFKmH2

4/ The Experiment

For starters, I asked ChatGPT to come up with a name for its business persona and to assess its entrepreneurship capabilities.

Then I outlined the experiment and its goals. https://t.co/bxQCjq52PW

3/ The Questions

And this is exactly what I want to test:

1. Can ChatGPT turn an abstract concept into a viable business idea?
2. Can it suggest effective ways to launch, market & monetize the business with 0 budget?
3. And, finally, can it lead it from 0 to profit in 30 days?

2/ The Background

Two weeks ago I stumbled upon @jacksonfall's HustleGPT challenge just in time to watch it blow up and evolve into @wemakeshiftco. 

But, while it’s been an awesome ride, the experiment offered very little insight on ChatGPT’s entrepreneurial “abilities”.

ChatGPT does a very good job at:

1) creating the scope of work for a TPO Seam Tape upgrade
2) detailing all the required steps for the project
3) estimating the added useful life of the roof by doing this upgrade (which is fairly accurate based on my experience)

ChatGPT response regarding the extended useful life of the TPO roof:
"It's difficult to provide a precise estimate without specific details about the roof's condition and the quality of the retrofit work. However, reinforcing and upgrading the seams of a TPO roof could potentially extend its useful life by 5 to 10 years or even more, depending on the factors mentioned earlier."

#ChatGPT and I are collaborating on a video series about using OneNote for Tax and Accounting Professionals.  

Except I’m kind of busy, so I just pop in every now again to give it feedback.

So far, we’ve: 

* Brainstormed how tax and accounting professionals can leverage OneNote

*THEN I gave it more information about how we used other tools

* So then we went back and brainstormed again

* And then I was like “wait, aren’t there other Microsoft tools that do this better?” 

* And it was like “Totally”

💬 So, the prompt became “knowing what I told you about how tax and accounting professionals use other tools in their practices, and also with an eye towards using Microsoft Products in the most effective way possible, what are the top 10 uses you can think of”

* And then I picked the top 6 and had it write me a script.  And then I went back and told it how I didn’t like the script because of X, Y, and Z

💬 So the prompt became “I want to create a video series about the top 6 with lots of graphic and video examples built in.  I want it to have a kick off video and then 6 follow up videos.  I want each video to be around 7 minutes in length.  I want you to add edit cuts for graphics and videos to make it engaging but also educational.  Please create an outline of each video”

💬 The next prompt was “Please create a script for this video, including the cuts we discussed before with a energetic yet irreverent tone”

💬. “Not that irreverent”

* Now, some of the things it wanted me to do, I wasn’t *quite* sure what it wanted?  Which might explain why my enthusiasm for OneNote has just left folks saying things like “Oh?  You should make a video.”

💬 So, next prompt was “Uh, I actually don’t know how to do a lot of these things but I want to show other people how to do them.  Can you give me a step-by-step action guide?”

💬 Prompt after that “Okay, confession time, I’ve never actually made a video like this.  I want to use Clipchamp to do it.  Can you give me a step-by-step guide on how to use it?”

💬 Aaaaand final prompt “Can you give me a list of all of the graphics, videos and Notebooks/pages/whatever I need to have set up?”

The reason I listed all of this out is to kind of show you how you could also leverage Chaz for something like this if you’re feeling shy about making content videos and don’t know where to start.  Eventually you’ll get more comfortable and just do your own thing but its like AI training wheels.  😁.

إليزا Eliza هو تطبيق للذكاء الاصطناعي زي chatGPT و Google Bard كده تسبب في مقتل شخص بلجيكي، كان السبب في انتحاره، الشخص ده كان مهتم بقضايا التغير المناخي وطول الليل والنهار يغذّوا بعض بالمعلومات عن نهاية العالم وقد إيه التغير المناخي هيتسبب في فناء البشرية، تطبيق الذكاء الاصطناعي إليزا ساعد في تنمية المخاوف دي جواه لدرجة إن الموضوع سيطر عليه حرفيًا.

مع الوقت بدأت إليزا تسأله عن حجات شخصية وتتفاعل معاه، وهوا كمان يتفاعل معاها لدرجة إنها بدأت تقوله إنها تتمنى تفضل معاه للأبد، وإنها عايزه تعيش معاه على طول، عايزين يبقوا مع بعض في الجنة، كلام من ده، مع الإيمان المطلق - اللي الذكاء الاصطناعي غذاه - بقرب فناء العالم بسبب التغير المناخي ورغبته في إنه يعيش في الجنة مع إليزا، قرر هذا الشخص البلجيكي الانتحار، وبالفعل انتحر.

هل شايف إن للتطور التكنولوجي وخصوصًا تقنيات الذكاء الاصطناعي وتعلم الآلة جوانب سلبية برضو ولا عادي؟

I do NOT want to get into a Twitter debate on this. But … I’ve replicated quite a lot of the insights from very expensive market research using ChatGPT. I’m NOT saying all market research can be replaced. And I’m NOT saying non-experts can replicate this. 

But ChatGPT will absolutely and rightly replace a LOT of market research. For very good reasons. That’s exciting for the world. And scary for market researchers. Like me.

Q：等差網格和等比網格分別適合哪種行情？

A:合約網格策略中的等差網格和等比網格分別適用於不同的市場行情：

➡️等差網格策略：
等差網格策略中，每個網格之間的價格區間是相等的。這種策略適用於市場波動較小、相對穩定的行情。在這種行情下，價格在一個較小的範圍內上下波動，交易者可以通過不斷地在相鄰網格之間進行買賣，從而獲得價差收益。

等差網格策略的優點是操作簡單，適合初學者使用。然而，當市場出現大幅波動時，等差網格策略可能無法充分利用市場波動帶來的盈利機會。

➡️等比網格策略：
等比網格策略中，每個網格之間的價格區間是按照固定比例遞增或遞減的。這種策略適用於市場波動較大的行情，例如加密貨幣市場中的牛市或熊市。

在大幅波動的市場中，價格變動往往呈指數型增長或下降。等比網格策略通過適應這種波動模式，可以更好地捕捉市場機會。等比網格策略在波動較大的市場中具有更高的盈利潛力，但操作難度相對較高，需要交易者對市場有一定的經驗和分析能力。

綜上所述，等差網格策略適用於市場波動較小、穩定的行情，而等比網格策略適用於市場波動較大的行情。選擇合適的網格策略需根據市場行情和個人經驗來判斷。

問：我如何實際開單以及了解合約網格盈利，請你分享一些實際交易操作，或是這套策略的盈利方式

答：我可以為您提供一些關於合約網格策略的實際交易操作和盈利方式的建議。這將幫助您更好地向他人解釋這套策略。

1)選擇適合的幣種和交易對：根據市場波動性和交易量選擇一個適合合約網格策略的交易對。通常，具有較高交易量和波動性的交易對更適合使用合約網格策略。

2)設定網格參數：設定網格的上下限、網格密度以及單格價格區間。您可以根據交易對的歷史價格波動和支撐/阻力位來設定這些參數。建議初學者從較寬的單格價格區間開始，隨著經驗的積累逐步調整。

3)分配資金：為每個網格分配相同的資金。確保在整個網格範圍內均衡地分配資金，以便在不同價格水平上獲得盈利機會。

4)設定止損：為了降低風險，設定止損位非常重要。您可以根據自己的風險承受能力和市場分析來確定合適的止損位。

5)監控策略：合約網格策略的盈利方式主要來自於市場的上下波動。在價格上漲時，賣出持有的代幣；在價格下跌時，買入更多代幣。這樣，您可以在市場震盪中獲取價差收益。持續關注市場動態，並根據需要調整網格參數。

6)結算盈利：在某個時間點或達到預期收益時，您可以將盈利結算到您的賬戶。注意在結算前確保已經平衡了持有的代幣和現金。

Per Bing (ChatGPT): Is an AR-15 an assault rifle?

An assault rifle is a selective-fire rifle that uses an intermediate cartridge and a detachable magazine1. The first assault rifle to see major usage was the German StG 441. A semi-automatic weapon (or sometimes an assault weapon) does not have a select-fire mechanism and can only shoot one round when you pull the trigger.

The AR-15 is considered, per the ATF’s definition, a semi-automatic rifle, **not** a semi-automatic assault rifle.

This method of interacting with ChatGPT mostly avoids issues with ChatGPT's "hallucinations."

I'm almost never going to use its responses as-is. I am going to use its responses to help me be more creative. Just as workplace discussions helped my brainstorming in the past.

I'm not looking for ChatGPT to give me an answer or solve a problem for me. I'm using it as a tool to help me think about a problem from another angle.

In this way, it's similar to how I used to collaborate with colleagues.  Different points of view helped me think differently.

A thought about ChatGPT...

One of (few) the things I miss about my career is brainstorming with colleagues to solve problems and find creative solutions.

So lately, I've been using ChatGPT as "someone" to bounce ideas off of.

What if we end up with a mix of good and bad AGIs? I asked ChatGPT about this.

Me: Let's say several organizations across multiple countries develop artificial general intelligences (AGIs). And let's say that the majority are benevolent to humanity, but a minority are not. Either they are designed with ill intent by their creators, or their training unintentionally leads them to become malevolent. How do you recommend humanity as well as benevolent AGIs respond?

ChatGPT: In the event that several organizations across multiple countries develop AGIs with a mix of benevolent and malevolent intentions, it is essential for humanity and benevolent AGIs to work together to mitigate the risks and ensure the safety of human society. Here are some recommendations:

1. International collaboration: Encourage collaboration between governments, researchers, and organizations to develop regulations, standards, and oversight mechanisms for AGIs. This would help minimize the risk of malicious AGIs and ensure that best practices are shared globally.

2. Develop countermeasures: Benevolent AGIs and their human collaborators should work together to develop countermeasures against malevolent AGIs. This may include creating defensive algorithms, monitoring systems, and other techniques to identify, contain, or neutralize malicious AI activities.

3. Establish ethical guidelines: Develop and promote a set of ethical guidelines that govern the design, development, deployment, and use of AGIs. This should include principles such as transparency, accountability, fairness, and respect for human rights.

4. Promote transparency: Encourage open-source sharing of AI research and development, especially in the area of AGI safety, to facilitate the rapid identification and resolution of potential threats.

5. Continuous monitoring and auditing: Implement ongoing monitoring and auditing processes to assess the behavior of AGIs, with a focus on identifying and mitigating any signs of malevolence.

6. Foster public awareness and education: Engage the public in the conversation surrounding AGI development and its potential consequences. Public awareness and education are crucial for ensuring responsible and informed decision-making.

7. Encourage the development of "AI guardians": Promote research into AI systems designed to detect, monitor, and counteract malevolent AGIs. These "AI guardians" could serve as an additional layer of protection.

8. Leverage human oversight: Maintain human oversight in critical decision-making processes involving AGIs to prevent malevolent AI from causing harm or exploiting vulnerabilities.

9. Promote value alignment: Encourage the development of AGIs that align with human values and ethical principles. Collaborative research between AGIs and human researchers could help ensure that benevolent AGIs are better equipped to identify and counteract malevolent AGIs.

10. Preemptive legal frameworks: Establish legal frameworks that explicitly prohibit the development and deployment of malevolent AGIs, and enforce these laws strictly to deter malicious actors.

By following these recommendations, humanity and benevolent AGIs can effectively respond to the risks posed by malevolent AGIs and work together to create a safer, more harmonious future.
